Asset Liability Management and Financial Structuring Officer
ESM - European Stability Mechanism
Luxembourg
Job description
Deadline for application:
21 August 2026
We are looking for an Asset Liability Management (ALM) and Financial Structuring Officer to contribute to the high-quality monitoring, analysis, and reporting of structural balance sheet risks (liquidity, interest rate, and foreign exchange) for the European Stability Mechanism (ESM) and its predecessor the European Financial Stability Facility (EFSF), as well as the analytical input for strategic institutional decision making. The role requires the use of data science tools and data analytics to develop, maintain, and utilise financial quantitative data-driven solutions. You will be expected to design and automate quantitative and reporting tools on key structural risk metrics. You will report to the Head of ALM and Financial Structuring.
Key Accountabilities
Monitor and analyse EFSF/ESM structural risks (liquidity, interest rate, and foreign exchange) and produce ALM reports;
Define appropriate strategies and instruments to mitigate risks arising from the EFSF/ESM’s liquidity profile;
Use data modelling techniques to compute, forecast, and optimise costs and risks for the ESM/EFSF and its beneficiary Member States;
Refine existing quantitative models and, if required, build new ones to efficiently and reliably forecast and measure the liquidity positions of EFSF/ESM or other financial risks;
Contribute to ALM’s advisory role by informing ESM management on main financial risk factors impacting EFSF/ESM balance sheets;
Support liquidity and collateral management by estimating potential future exposure for a derivatives portfolio using different analytical techniques;
Work closely with various internal divisions to integrate multiple layers of information to produce critical ESM strategic advice to support senior management.
Key Background & Experience
Advanced university degree or specialisation in a quantitative field (finance, economics, computer science, engineering, or mathematics or equivalent);
Ideally, between one to five years of relevant experience in ALM, investment, treasury, and/or risk management, preferably acquired in a financial services environment;
Solid data analysis skills, statistics, and quantitative analysis skills;
Knowledge of financial data modelling, financial risk concepts, financial derivatives, and risk management techniques;
Ability to code in Python, R, VBA, or another programming language;
Knowledge of relational databases (Microsoft SQL server, MySQL, SQLite);
GIT knowledge for code and control versioning;
Experience with business intelligence tools and concepts (Microsoft Power BI and/or Tableau);
Experience with Microsoft Office Suite (Excel, Word, PowerPoint);
A professional qualification, such as FRM, CFA, CQF, ECDL Certificate or similar would be an asset;
Excellent oral and written communication skills in English. Any additional languages are an asset.
Key Competencies
Analytical and problem-solving skills;
Critical thinking and innovative mindset;
Communication and interpersonal skills;
Resilience, flexibility, and adaptability;
Team spirit oriented and collaborative;
Inclusive and respectful of diversity;
Developing self and others.
Application Process And Practical Information
Deadline for applications: 21 August 2026;
Number of vacancies: two vacancies available;
Expected start date: as soon as possible;
Contract type: two-year fixed-term contract;
Contractual terms: Roles are offered on a fixed-term basis, with no assurance of extension or renewal;
Place of employment: Luxembourg;
Current working arrangements: possibility to work remotely, usually up to two days a week, from Luxembourg and the border region (or from further away under certain conditions).
The ESM aims to provide equal opportunity to all candidates irrespective of their gender, nationality, age, race, culture, education, religious beliefs, sexual orientation, or disability. To further enhance the diversity of our workforce, we particularly encourage women to apply.
Note 1:
the ESM reserves the right to refrain from hiring, or to slightly modify job responsibilities, as needed.
Note 2:
As a result of the selection process, please note that you may be placed on a ‘reserve list’ valid for a duration of six months during which you might be considered for a similar position with a similar level of requirements. Only those candidates who have been notified will be placed on the ‘reserve list’. After this period, you will need to apply again for our vacancies to be considered for a different selection process.
About us
The European Stability Mechanism (ESM) is the permanent crisis resolution mechanism for euro area countries. It provides financial assistance to Members facing financing difficulties. To date, the ESM and its predecessor organisation, the European Financial Stability Facility (EFSF), have launched six financial assistance programmes to five countries, provided financial support, monitored repayment capacity, and engaged with partner institutions for programme design in areas of financial interest.
The ESM is a unique place to work with around 230 individuals committed to making a difference to the future of the euro area. It recruits talented professionals of any nationality from both the private and public sectors. The ESM’s senior management is committed to preserving and enhancing a diverse, inclusive recruitment and work environment.
